%S A397084 2,23,223,2203,22003,220013,2200013,20200013,202002013,2032002013,
%T A397084 20032002013,200302002013,2003020020013,20030200020013,
%U A397084 200302000201013,2003020002001013,20030200020001013,202030200020001013,2021030200020001013,20210530200020001013,202100530200020001013,2002100530200020001013
%N A397084 Start with a(1) = 2; to get a(n+1) insert in a(n) the smallest possible digit at the leftmost possible position such that the new number is a prime.
%C A397084 This is the left-right counterpart of A357436. It uses the same precedence of smallness of the inserted digit over the insertion position, but considers positions from left to right instead of from right to left.
%C A397084 Together with A356557, A357436, and A397083, this sequence belongs to the family obtained by choosing the precedence between digit smallness and insertion position, and the direction in which insertion positions are considered.
%C A397084 Smallness of the inserted digit has precedence over leftmostness of its position.
%C A397084 Prepending a 0 is not allowed.
%C A397084 If no prime extension exists, the sequence terminates.
%C A397084 a(n) has n decimal digits.
%C A397084 The sequence terminates if and only if it contains a term of A125001.
%C A397084 Is the sequence infinite?
%H A397084 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A397084/b397084.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%e A397084 a(2) = 23. Starting from a(1) = 2, insertion positions are considered from left to right for each digit. The numbers 20, 21, 22 are composite, while 23 is prime.
%e A397084 a(7) = 2200013. Starting from a(6) = 220013, insertion of the digit 0 is tested from left to right. Prepending 0 is not allowed; 2020013 is composite, while 2200013 is prime.
%t A397084 a[1]=2; a[n_]:=a[n]=Catch@Block[{p, d = IntegerDigits[a[n - 1]]},Do[p=FromDigits@Insert[d,c,i]; If[p>a[n-1]&&PrimeQ[p],Throw[p]],{c,0,9},{i,1,1+Length[d]}]]; Array[a, 22]
%o A397084 (Python)
%o A397084 from sympy import isprime
%o A397084 from itertools import islice
%o A397084 def anext(an):
%o A397084     s = str(an)
%o A397084     for c in "0123456789":
%o A397084         for k in range(int(c=="0"), len(s)+1):
%o A397084             w = s[:k] + c + s[k:]
%o A397084             if isprime(int(w)): return int(w)
%o A397084 def agen(an=2):
%o A397084     while an != None: yield an; an = anext(an)
%o A397084 print(list(islice(agen(), 22))) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jun 16 2026
%Y A397084 Cf. A357436, the right-to-left counterpart, in which smallness of the inserted digit also has precedence over the insertion position.
%Y A397084 Cf. A397083, which also considers insertion positions from left to right, but gives precedence to leftmostness of position over smallness of the inserted digit.
%Y A397084 Cf. A356557, in which rightmostness of position has precedence over smallness of the inserted digit.
%Y A397084 Cf. A125001, A332603.
%K A397084 nonn,base,new
%O A397084 1,1
%A A397084 _Bartlomiej Pawlik_, Jun 16 2026
